mework of human rights is locally interpreted, constituted, and contested in Harare, Zimbabwe, and Musina and Cape Town, South Africa. Presenting the stories of those who lived through the violent struggles of the past decades, Morreira shows how supposedly universal ideals become localized in the context of post-colonial Southern Africa. Rights After Wrongs uncovers the disconnect between the ways human rights appear on paper and the ways in which it is possible for people to use and understand them in everyday life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHuman rightsxAnthropological aspectszZimbabwe. 0aInternational law and human rightszZimbabwe. 0aZimbabweansxCivil rightszSouth Africa. 4aHuman rights. 4aZimbabwe. 4acivil society. 4acoloniality. 4aethnography. 4ajustice. 4alegal anthropology. 4apolitical violence. 4apostcolonialism. 4astructural violence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479909640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799096423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799096.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles